## Conversation
User reported Chrome console spam blowing up the tab during gameplay, plus
stuttering with many cursors moving fast. Suspected Supabase Realtime / live
cursors. Asked me to dispatch agents to map the codebase and discuss.

After agents reported, I framed three levers (cursor state-out-of-React,
broadcast throttle, useCountdown background-pause). User mentioned a stress
script "scripts/bots.ts" and asked if we could simulate cursors with it.
Implemented + ran 10 bots into room GNTP — confirmed working. Then user
asked for chat-message sending; added that and was about to relaunch when
GNTP had already started so bots couldn't join. User pasted a fresh code
ETZR, bots flooded chat + cursors fine.

Then user dumped the actual console output. Smoking gun:
> Multiple GoTrueClient instances detected ... :2099, :2100, :2101 ...

The instance counter was incrementing ~10/sec. That's the cause of the
"console spam blows up Chrome" problem — not loop logging, not realtime
warnings, but thousands of GoTrueClients all listening on the same
auth-token storage key.

Found it: lib/supabase/client.ts had two factories (`createSupabaseBrowserClient`
for data, `createSupabaseAuthBrowserClient` for auth/SSR) that constructed
a fresh client every call. The killer was `useRef(createSupabaseBrowserClient())`
in game-client.tsx (3x) and host-controls.tsx — useRef's argument runs on
every render, and the 250ms useCountdown drives ~4 renders/sec, so 12 fresh
clients/sec just from those refs.

User said "push to prod bro." Shipping via PR per their established flow
(memory: deploy via PR merge, not vercel CLI).

