## Hints for Future Agents
- The browser supabase client architecture is unusual: vanilla
  `@supabase/supabase-js` for data, `@supabase/ssr` only for auth/cookie
  flows. AGENTS.md explains why (the ssr browser client has a getSession
  hang). Don't "simplify" by collapsing them.
- BOTH factories now return module-scope singletons. Calling them from
  events / effects / refs is fine; they're idempotent.
- Module scope per JS context = per page-load, so a hard navigation gets
  a fresh client which then re-reads the auth cookie. Soft navigations
  reuse the singleton — which is correct because the cookie hasn't
  changed.
- room-channel.tsx's 25-min `realtime.setAuth(token)` refresh still
  works correctly because there's now a stable singleton's realtime
  socket to update. Before this fix, refreshing one client's auth had
  no effect on the dozen newly-constructed siblings.
- scripts/bots.ts can simulate cursors AND chat. Use --no-cursors /
  --no-chat / --cursor-hz / --chat-interval to isolate stress tests.
  Bots fail to join if the room is past lobby — they need a fresh code.

## Codebase Discoveries
- `useRef(expensiveCall())` is a React anti-pattern that bites hard:
  the constructor runs every render even though only the first value is
  kept. Common fix: useRef(null) + lazy-init in an effect, OR
  useState(() => expensiveCall())[0]. We didn't refactor those callers
  because the singleton makes the hot constructor a no-op now.
- The user-menu.tsx initial render runs createSupabaseAuthBrowserClient()
  inside a useEffect once per mount. UserMenu lives in the root layout, so
  it runs once per page load — not per render. Why was it triggering the
  warning so much? Probably because the OLD un-memoized data factory was
  constructing dozens of supabase-js clients per second, and each one's
  GoTrueClient sees the storage key and emits the warning. The ssr-auth
  client is innocent volume-wise; both are fixed by this commit anyway.

